# Markdown Documentation Rules

## Critical Rule

**Do not create markdown documentation files unless the user explicitly
asks for them.** This applies to every code task — bug fixes, refactors,
feature work, code reviews, dependency upgrades, anything. If the user
hasn't asked for docs, don't write docs.

When the user does ask, follow the rules below.

---

## File Placement

- The repository root may contain only `README.md`.
- Every other markdown file lives under `/docs/`.
- Use kebab-case names: `api-reference.md`, `code-review-report.md`.
  Avoid generic names like `notes.md` or `temp.md`.

```
project-root/
├── README.md           # only md allowed at the root
└── docs/               # everything else
    ├── api-reference.md
    ├── deployment-guide.md
    ├── troubleshooting.md
    └── …
```

---

## Document Structure

Use a clear hierarchy:

```markdown
# Title

One-line description of what this covers.

## Overview

- Purpose and scope
- Prerequisites

## Main content

### Section 1
…

### Section 2
…

## Examples

…

## References

…
```

Required sections: **Title**, **Overview**, content sections, and
**References** when relevant. Add a TOC for documents long enough to scroll.

---

## Content Style

- Active voice, concise sentences.
- Use bullet lists / numbered steps for procedures.
- Code blocks must include a language tag (`ts`, `bash`, `jsonc`, …).
- Internal links use relative paths (`./other-doc.md`); external links use
  full URLs.
- Keep terminology consistent with the codebase (e.g. "Route Handler", not
  "API endpoint" / "function").

---

## Updates and Migrations

- When code changes, update **existing** docs that describe that code.
  Do not create new docs to "log" the change.
- If you move a markdown file into `/docs/`, update every link that
  pointed at the old path (search the repo, including other `.md` files
  and code comments).

---

## When the User Asks for Documentation

Examples that qualify as explicit requests:

- "Write a code review report for the recent changes"
- "Generate API documentation for `/api/billing/*`"
- "Create a deployment guide for the queue workers"

For these, place the new file under `/docs/<kebab-case-name>.md`, follow
the structure above, and link it from any existing index doc if one
exists.

If the request is ambiguous (e.g. "document this"), ask whether they want
new docs or just inline JSDoc / comments — see
`clarification-before-action.mdc`.
